Anyone who smokes has a higher risk of losing teeth.
Smoking damages not only the lungs, but also the teeth - this is suggested by a long-term study in Potsdam.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk will go down quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is the result of a long-term study by an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DifE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at 2.5 to 3.6 times higher risk of losing their teeth prematurely.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth failure are caries and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The association between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is unclear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the danger to drop back to the level of non-smokers, explained first author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham in England.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, study leader Heiner Boeing of the DIfE explained: "Smoking shortens lifespan."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years is affected by dental insanity, the DIfE reported.
Previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
