Pounds rise due to accelerated wage growth in the UK
The pound rose sharply following data showing an increase in UK wage growth, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the SABMiller bid target.
Between May and July, earnings without bonuses in the United Kingdom grew by 2.9% compared to the same period of the previous year.
This percentage has been the fastest and most accurate estimate of the timing of an interest rate increase since 2009.
The pound rose by more than 1% against the dollar to $1,5505 and climbed to 0.84% against the euro to €1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed with a 1.49% increase to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the outstanding share in the market and made a 20% jump after a takeover bid from rival AB InBev.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher, according to encouraging news from the rival luxury goods group Richemont.
Richemont’s latest sales figures beat all expectations and also showed sales in China – a key market for Burberry – reported growth again.
Glencore shares rose 5% after the mining giant said it took $2.5 billion from a share sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
The shares of the packaging and paper company Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, down 4.3% after Goldman Sachs set its rating rating to "sell".
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax profit of 46.6 million for the half-year.
The head of JD Sports says higher wages are jeopardizing expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean “more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers.”
But it is unlikely that this purchasing power will offset the higher labor costs at his company, he says.
The costs could hit JD Sports’ expansion plans, he added, and that could mean there are fewer additional jobs.
