Metcash launches ground-level campaign to combat Aldi invasion
Metcash is trying to protect IGA stores from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a down-to-earth campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA Supermarkets strengthen their relationships with local food suppliers and build the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide Show.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands like ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough distributing samples at IGA stores and store owners selling discounted South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on Sept. 29 as the food, alcohol and appliance wholesaler conducts its annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away around five percent of the food market in these two states and take away sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in annual sales and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that next year Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA and achieve revenues of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery store and the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash’s revenue in the food and grocery business will fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and will reduce market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr. Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a board member of Metcash contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenues from Metcash’s food and grocery trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while putting pressure on revenue and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back and investing more than $150 million to align selling prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores through fast-growing fresh foods and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash’s chief executive, Ian Morrice, says price adjustments and store refurbishment programs will increase, hoping that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by the president of the Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the “collateral damage” in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior, according to Australian tennis federation president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the youngest of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as the "Special Ks", came into the spotlight through Kyrgios' infamous confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison shouting, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a spasm defeated a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
“One thing I’m getting pretty excited about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi got pulled into the fight a little bit,” Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost to a bump in the U.S. Open, but he’s not the first player to break a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he did extremely well at the US Open, even under the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He’s got a great team around him, he’s got a great family around him, and I think he’s been treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the changing room, he trains hard, he is good in shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to consider Kyrgios in the important preliminary decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the Canberra man of returning to the team as a long-term permanent component."
“First of all, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not all the controversies around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I think Nick made the ascent very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He is rising in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time out of the spotlight, I think it is best for him to think about it, and it is only in the light of what he is doing.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds refugees back
Hungary declared a state of emergency, locked the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday and detained all those trying to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed on the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man country and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled from violence stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustration increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted “Open the border!” and shouted insults against the Hungarian police on standby.
Some rejected food and water out of protest.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants would be sent back from Hungary as more and more migrants arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution, not collateral damage.
There will have to be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days,” Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The turbulence on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc could not agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
However, the ministers agreed to share the responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the overwhelmed Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually – next month or by the end of the year – an agreement would be reached that EU countries would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special summit of the European Union to discuss the immigration crisis of the continent.
However, Hungary did not put its hopes on an early action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Meanwhile, Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country is also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence at the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck and entry point to the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the incoming economic refugees are in search of a better life, not war refugees who are entitled to protection – a view that is strongly at odds with other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime, and also impose higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
“Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency,” government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to agree to the military’s expected deployment next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers carrying vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, state security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a barbed wire train arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pressed a crowd to push themselves into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main motorway link between Serbia and Hungary, saying they would deny food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
Election 2016: Hillary Clinton’s lead over Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders wins on the ground.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the pre-election (58 percent previously), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, receives support from 15 percent of Democratic voters in the pre-elections.
More than five months before the start of the pre-elections, most Democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion is certain which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some gains.
Clinton holds a big lead among women and moderates, but those advances have diminished.
Their support for the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind here.
Clinton’s advantage among Democratic voters under the age of 50 has vanished, and she and Sanders are now on an equal footing.
Clinton still has a strong lead among older voters.
Last month, Clinton was two-way ahead of Sanders in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a five-point lead in that group.
About half of Democratic voters in the country’s pre-elections say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would support her just because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed among those who do not currently support Clinton – only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of Democratic pre-election voters say they support Clinton enthusiastically, fewer Republican voters say so about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked on an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she’s the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mentioned her connection to Bill Clinton (9%).
Consent to dealing with the problems and selectability are also cited.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidency into the balance, 57 percent of Democratic pre-election voters want to see him in the race — even though a third believe he shouldn’t.
When Democratic voters in the pre-election are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
Of Clinton’s supporters, more than half say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead over Sanders increases from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chance of winning the election; however, that number has dropped by 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second in this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the “most selectable” has risen.
Nevertheless, when asking what is more important in a candidate, Democratic voters call questions about electability.
Similar to last month, no single Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable to these voters in the primaries.
Democratic candidates or potential candidates perform well on some important characteristics of voters in their party's primary.
Majorities view Clinton, Sanders and Biden as honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership skills.
Biden scores best in honesty among the three candidates, while Clinton’s strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don’t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent have no opinion of him.
Democratic voters in the pre-elections generally also view Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all these measurements, about a quarter of Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions continue about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server during her tenure as Secretary of State, most Democratic voters in the pre-elections are satisfied with her statement of the matter and say it has not influenced their views overall.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this issue was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their overall views of Clinton, though 36 percent said their views of her had worsened.
It’s mainly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is seen as honest and trustworthy by her party’s voters, this remains a problem for her among registered voters altogether: Only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month, and 15 points less since May.
62% of voters do not consider them to be honest and trustworthy.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also view Trump as not honest and untrustworthy.
However, Clinton and Trump get good marks on leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush score best in honesty.
A majority consider Sanders to be honest, but as with Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the pre-election elections is 6 percentage points.
Ben Carson gets close behind Donald Trump in nationwide poll
Ben Carson is behind Donald Trump in the latest CBS News/New York Times poll
The two candidates now account for half of the voter support in the new poll, and others dramatically lose hold
Republican voters continue to support Trump in large numbers nationwide, up 23% in the most recent CBS poll conducted before Fox News debate last month, up 27% in Tuesday’s poll.
But Carson shot from 6% to 23% in the same period.
The poll also found that Carson is well received by demographic groups and outperforms Trump among Republican voters with higher education.
The rest of the field, with the exception of Carly Fiorina and Ohio Governor John Kasich, has been cut off with Wisconsin Governor Scott Walker, who has fallen the lowest, from 10% support last month to 2% now.
Former Florida Governor Jeb Bush, former Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee and Florida Senator Marco Rubio are in third place with 6%.
The margin of error in the sample of 376 people from Republican voters in this latest poll is plus or minus 6% and was conducted in September.
The latest CNN/ORC poll released last week shows Carson is on the rise in polls — he lands at 19% support among Republicans, behind Trump with 32% support.
The latest ABC News/Washington Post poll also showed Trump clearly ahead of Carson.
Looking at a Carson rising last week, Trump found some side-slashes for the former neurosurgeon, even after Carson apologized for questioning Trump’s beliefs.
“We need energy,” Trump said last Saturday during a campaign appearance in Iowa.
