Five Brotherhood members burdened with death of Baruch College novice
Nearly two years after a student died during a harassing ritual of a student connection in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, charges are filed against five people.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transportation to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was blindfolded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked as he tried to approach a target over a frozen field.
Mr. Deng finally complained about headaches, then he fell unconscious.
Members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng fainted and were reportedly waiting an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms and contact Andy Meng, the Brotherhood’s national president, for advice, Police Chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and put the well-being of the Brotherhood fundamentally above that of Michael Deng," police chief Wagner said.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly injured with blunt force to the head, torso and thighs.
“Too many families have been destroyed by the Brotherhood’s harassment; at least one student has died of harassment every year since 1970,” Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng’s family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this step of authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended an indictment for third-degree murder for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassing attacks and forming a criminal association.
"We not only want to hold the people involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has sanctioned this - officially or unofficially - we will also hold them accountable," Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its membership in the local group.
This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the uptick will be shaken, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will last and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
As a result, Central Bank representatives have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when they start raising interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that the whole excitement about an interest rate increase may have been exaggerated.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the ‘cheap money’ era,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to clients.
By contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still at too low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a look at how some sectors of the economy might respond based on historical trends:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase arrives, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a trend that income will be stifled 12 to 24 months after the first increase, perhaps again reflecting the delay in monetary policy,” German bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
More specifically, over the past 35 years, the market is mostly on the upward trend - about 14 percent - on the way to a rate hike, quite flat in the 250 days thereafter (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return on the past six past cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a current analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment manager at Nu Doll's Investments.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the rise cycle and the return begins to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is noteworthy that gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point if the Fed raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, the nominal GDP of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 was only twice below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic environment could be risky and raise the question “whether this time is different,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been gearing up for a year-round Fed interest rate hike, and all eyes have been on this week’s Federal Open Market Committee meeting that ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all the increase cycles from 1950 to the present took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and overshadowed pre-recession levels very quickly after recovery began,” the report said.
In contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that in the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
With bonds, the returns seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields drop immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to shrink closer and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-income bonds often yield better returns in such a climate, although “we are still cautious about expecting higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones says, markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“Besides the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have widened and volatility has risen – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
Overall, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit when interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational corporations with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market, as well as financing their debt.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to respond overwhelmingly positively three months after an initial interest rate hike,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet have surpassed companies with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low stock volatility also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains from higher earnings, even if experts disagree on how fast this will happen.
BBC Radio 3 is a copy of Classic FM, says MP Andrew Bingham
The Conservative member of parliament criticized the station for its "dumbness"
He argues that he is increasingly indistinguishable from commercial rivals.
He also targeted the BBC Music Awards, saying that they only imitated The Brits.
Parliamentary colleague Damien Collins attacked The Voice, saying it was not very original.
BBC Radio 3 "turns" into Classic FM, a leading member of parliament claims, raising new pressure on the station to prove it is doing something that private broadcasters are not doing.
