At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide if it’s time to raise interest rates for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening above them is a mural of the United States at one end of the ornate, two-storey meeting room.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests above all other things.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the great recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X-factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned by the unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed representatives to increase this volatility by raising interest rates on federal bonds – even if only by a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the job market and inflation will be the most important thing they are seeing,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the heightened uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to keep waiting,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is inconsistent with the financial market.
About half of economists polled recently by Bloomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far from it.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that the Fed policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed lifted the rates at that time,” he said.
If it does, “it should go very far in its statement to calm the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen had said in spring and early summer that despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed, she expected an increase in the rate this year.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was consistently below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, the Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary impact of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world tumbled at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell more than 16% below its peak in May when investors feared a slowdown in China’s economy would stifle global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the May high.
For Fed representatives, market turbulence influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would be taking the reins in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, Senior Research Fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Federal Reserve.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better control the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” said Oliner.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere hint of then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “tighten” its monetary expansion triggered confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of the global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA., noted this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that appear to be unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, who is advocating for an interest rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia prompted the Fed to lower its interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three meetings “despite limited noticeable effects on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
Recent turbulence does not come close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into the situation where she’s afraid of a rate hike because markets are getting upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and doesn’t mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should move ahead of time.
