Marko Maksimovic, 29, was one of five men arrested last month after federal police found 100 kg of the drug on the yacht Solay, which came from South America over Vanuatu and landed in Coomera in August.
Maksimovic was observed meeting his fellow defendants in the marina during the morning and later at the Coomera Roadhouse Café, where police found 40 kilograms of the drug in a Toyota Echo.
Despite a potentially life sentence for attempting to possess a commercial amount of cocaine, Maksimovic’s lawyer argued that there was no evidence that he was trying to own the entire amount and that it could have been in the café for an innocuous reason.
Supreme Court judge Peter Flanagan was concerned about Maksimovic’s risk of escape.
He has clear relations with Serbia.
He often travels to Serbia,” he told the court on Wednesday.
In the criminal case, he lied to the police about his whereabouts.
Maksimovic’s mother and stepfather had offered a $200,000 security deposit together to secure his release.
“After reading the affidavits of the two individuals, it is clear that the requirement of a security of $200,000 represents a real financial burden,” Flanagan said.
But that alone will not be enough to keep him from not appearing, he warned.
Maksimovic was released on bail, on the condition that he surrender his Australian and Serbian passport, report to the police daily, and stick to an exit lock from 18:00-06:00.
