JVA Berlin-Tegel: Five-square-meter cell is unworthy of humankind
The Federal Constitutional Court gave a right to an ex-prisoner from the Tegel Prison, who was housed in a cell that was too small for months.
Because of the violation of their human dignity, prisoners are generally entitled to financial compensation if they are housed in cells that are too small.
This was decided by the Federal Constitutional Court in a decision published on Wednesday.
According to the judges, those affected can hope for money even if they were locked up for only a few days in the tight rooms (Az.: 1 BvR 1127/14).
With this, an ex-prisoner was successful with his constitutional complaint in Karlsruhe: he was housed in the Berlin-Tegel Prison between June and November 2009 in a single cell with about five square meters of floor area; the toilet was not separated spatially.
Afterwards, the man, who according to his lawyer is now back on his feet, had been moved to a larger cell.
His imprisonment lawsuit for the unworthy conditions of detention against the state of Berlin failed.
However, the constitutional judges set aside the judgment of the Berlin Chamber Court and dismissed the case for further examination there.
You see the man's human dignity hurt.
Court of First Instance now decides on the amount of compensation
Even if, for legal reasons, from the period in question only a few days of imprisonment were decisive for the compensation, there was a claim for compensation, it said.
Otherwise, it would be “a deterioration of the legal protection of the personality.”
The court must now determine the amount of the compensation.
In the past, constitutional judges have often strengthened the rights of prisoners.
For example, they did not award damages to a prisoner until April because he was locked up in a cell naked.
According to a 2011 decision, the multiple occupancy of a cell without a separate toilet is also unworthy of humans.
Karlsruhe also confirmed on Wednesday the Berlin Constitutional Court, which had attested to a prisoner in a parallel case in November 2009 an inhumane accommodation.
The plaintiff was housed in a cell of the same kind as in the Karlsruhe case for three months between 15 and 21 hours a day.
Berlin prisons have also made headlines in recent weeks due to a lack of staff.
Prisoners are therefore locked up again and again for 23 hours, aggression increases, even fights are said to have already occurred because of the tense situation.
According to the judicial press office, 21 jobs in Tegel have not been filled due to a shortage of young talent, 19 are expected to be eliminated in 2016.
