FriendsFest: the comedy show that gives us serious lessons about men’s friendships
The lack of similar depictions in shows is obvious, especially in view of how the need for men to open up has now become even more desperate than ever, as suicide rates among young men at a 15-year high prove.
In 2013, it was the leading cause of death in men aged 20 to 45 in the UK, and it remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an effort to address the problem, the Campaign Against Living Miserably announced 2015 as the Year of the Man, with the aim of challenging the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the struggle to overcome this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with depressive symptoms found that if the sufferer had a sufficiently high percentage of friends with "healthy mood," his chances of recovery doubled.
For those who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halves the risks of mental problems.
But, of course, you have to have friends first in order for a friendship to work.
In the age of communication conducted through social media, with its emphasis on style over substance, the immediacy of the response is often more important than meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to appear strong, lively and successful, even if in reality isolation dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the expense of intrinsic values – our inner longing for personal development and friendship, which has a much deeper impact on our mental health.
And as a video game inventor and billionaire recently explained, money really can’t buy luck.
The nice thing about Friends was that this focus was turned upside down.
Each character was defined not by his work, but by his personality, which shone as a friend through the interaction.
The humour of Joey and Chandler’s frequent hugs, moments of football watching in cozy armchairs, and Ross’ longing for Rachel – all came from the knowledge that men can definitely refer to it, even if they often shy away from fully exploring their feelings.
As a phone counselor explained to me, “my listening role for people who feel depressed and at risk of suicide really showed me how even the smallest interactions of friends can make a difference.”
The men who contact us often feel unable to talk to friends.
The old phrase "I can handle it" has an enormous effect, such as the feeling that it is perceived as a weakness when you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term coping mechanisms.
It clearly presents the small moments of men's friendships.
As much as my objective outsider status over the phone may help people in moments of despair, the long-term support comes from a personal network of family and friends.
And so, if you visit Comedy Central FriendsFest this weekend with the completely redesigned backdrop to celebrate the day, why not take your friends for a drink at Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone sitting around alone in Starbucks, give them a smile and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship could make.
