Xi pushes to open up the economy to the world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday to a group tasked with steering the reform.
“China should be committed to attracting foreign investment and know-how and improving business start-up strategies,” he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Fostering new start-ups and driving reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list to regulate market access, relaxation of border control policy, promotion of state enterprises (SOE), incorporation of private capital, and overhaul of the resident reporting system.
After the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by testing programs.
The initiative is important as it assigns a greater role to the market in allocating resources, ensures a legal-state business environment, and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also ease controls on the powers conferred on companies and ensure that companies decide how they conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open state-controlled sectors, further areas for private investment will be opened.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of third-party financed companies and provide better services to them,” the statement said.
In addition, it is made easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
