EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limits for mercury in large predatory fish, giving consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding working paper from the EU, sharply criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on with full force to pregnant women and young children," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve agent for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predators are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold on the basis of the limits still in force.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsold.
In return for this easing, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch described this as a "trick" because smaller friedfish, such as carp, are usually so low that they already meet the planned maximum values today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore “a perfidious distraction maneuver that helps the economy alone,” Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and is highly enriched throughout the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The German government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn babies."
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment states on its homepage that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the burning of coal.
According to a written report from the German Federal Ministry for the Environment, German coal power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and comprehensively exceeded", the "Spiegel" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, pan-European mercury warnings in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.mercury-aktion.foodwatch.de
